For programming it is better to use the standard subsetting functions like [, #(lf)###(tab)#(tab)#(tab) and in particular the non-standard evaluation of argument subset can have unanticipated consequences.""#(lf)data_funded_sig_all <- lapply(sig_areas_char, function(x)#(lf)  subset(data_funded0, Signature.Area == x, select = c(Source, Target))#(lf))#(lf)names(data_funded_sig_all) <- sig_areas_char#(lf)#(lf)bigdata <- graph_from_data_frame(data_funded_sig_all$`Data Analytics/Big Data/Data Science/Data Visualization`)#(lf)#energydata <- graph_from_data_frame(data_funded_sig_all$`Energy/Resilient Infrastructure`)#(lf)#(lf)## create metrics for all#(lf)bigDataTotalDegree <- degree(bigdata, mode = ""all"")#(lf)bigDataTotalDegree <- as.data.frame(bigDataTotalDegree)#(lf)bigDataTotalDegree <- cbind(Row.Names = rownames(bigDataTotalDegree), bigDataTotalDegree)#(lf)#(lf)#(lf)## now create new data frame with all source and target names no duplications#(lf)#(lf)temp1 <- as.vector(data_funded0$Source)#(lf)temp2 <- as.vector(data_funded0$Target)#(lf)temp3 <- append(temp1, temp2)#(lf)Faculty <- as.data.frame(temp3)#(lf)Faculty <- unique(Faculty$temp3)#(lf)Faculty <- as.data.frame(Faculty)"),
